<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-795-824  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 795 824.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Sept 26 1989 v3 n34 p89(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple cited as a top-ten company for working mothers. (BusinessBriefs)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (personnel management).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     Personnel ManagementSurveyFamiliesSalaryEmployee BenefitsWomen.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Apple cited as a top-ten company for working mothersandM;New York -- Apple is the apple of the working mother's eye, according to asurvey conducted by Working Mother magazine.andP;  Apple made the top ten among 60companies selected by the magazine as &quot;the best companies for working mothersin 1989.&quot; Criteria included pay, advancement opportunities, child care andbenefits, the magazine said.andM;Apple was cited for its on-site child care and educational center.andP;  Thecenter serves 70 children, with a waiting list of 150, and costs $425 to $664per month.andM;The article, published in the October issue, also pointed to the company'spractice of giving $500 to each employee's new baby and offering $3,000 inaid to prospective adoptive parents.andM;On a scale of 1 to 5, Apple received the top rank of 5 in salary and childcare, 4 in benefits and 3 in advancement opportunities.andP;  By comparison, IBM-- which also ranked in the top ten -- matched Apple in salary, bested it inbenefits and trailed in career advancement and child care.andM;Among other computer-related companies in the magazine's fourth annual surveywere Digital Equipment Corp., Hewlett-Packard, SAS Institute Inc. and XeroxCorp.andO;</TEXT></DOC>